						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">blargg wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Famicom Titler?</div><br />I'm guessing this is some kind of video titler built around a Famicom. Are you suggesting I name one of them "Famicom Titler"? Seems kind of obscure.</div><br />I seem to remember that the <a href="http://hawanja.com/famicom_titler.htm" class="postlink">Famicom Titler could output S-Video</a>.<br /></div>
<br />
<br />Yes the Famicom Titler is a much sought after version of the Famicom.  It is an official 3rd party clone, which supports S-video.  <a href="http://www.gamechoiceclub.com/navigateProduct.asp?product_id=544" class="postlink">Game Choice Club still sells Titlers</a>, but for a heft sum.  So in a sense, there is official NES hardware out there that can do S-video and RGB, i.e., the Titler and the arcade systems respectively.
<br />
<br />However, implementing optimizations, such as MMX seems to be more important right now.  If the filter can be made extremely fast, then you could have your cake and eat it to, for a new low low price <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />  That would virtually cement NTSC RGB as the default video setting in emulators like Nestopia.</div>

