					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">some people claim that the artifacts in PAL are pretty much invisible;</div>The PAL NES' pixels look like NTSC locked into one particular field's position --- thus, you get "hanging dots" instead of dot crawl (broadcast NTSC or NTSC NES with BG off) or jittery dots (normal NTSC NES). What some laypeople mean is that there is no visible "movement" with regards to the pixels (unlike on the NTSC NES), because a pixel's position relative to the color reference signal does not change from field to field (in  other words, the number of color clocks per field is an integer number).<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">What slider settings would produce a correct image for PAL?</div>Hue = minus 15 degrees. Don't know how many pixels that is on some emulators' blind sliders. Nestopia 1.28 has the PAL hues at the centered position, which I already criticized on the Nestopia board.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I figure some games must have been designed with PAL artifacts in mind, if the games were only going to be released in PAL.</div>European SMB 1. The NTSC SMB1 avoids scrolling the same number of pixels per field when running fast because that would expose the dot crawl. The PAL SMB1 does scroll the same number of pixels per field when running fast because on PAL, that HIDES the dot crawl.
<br />Basically, the NTSC NES looks clean with still images and dirty during scrolling; the PAL NES is the opposite.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

